'''Rebecca Kellogg Ashley''' (December 22, 1695 &ndash; August 1757)<ref>{{cite web|title=Rebecca Kellogg Ashley|url=https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/112646065|website=findagrave.com|accessdate=May 26, 2015}}</ref> was an English child captured by allied French, Canadian militia, [[Iroquois]], and [[Algonquin people|Algonquin]] soldiers in the 1704 [[Raid on Deerfield|Deerfield Raid]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Coleman|first=Emma|title=New England Captives Carried to Canada Between 1677 and 1760, During the French and Indian Wars|date=1925|publisher=Southworth Press|location=Portland, Oregon|page=43}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|first=Evan |last=Haefeli|first2= Kevin|last2= Sweeney|title=Captive histories: English, French, and Native narratives of the 1704 Deerfield raid|date=2006|publisher=[[University of Massachusetts Press]]|isbn=9781558495432}}</ref> The Deerfield attack was part of the decade-long [[Queen Anne's War]] (the 1702-1713 [[War of Spanish Succession]] on the Continent). Rebecca was eight years old. [[Eunice Kanenstenhawi Williams|Eunice Williams]] was captured in this same raid, as was her father, the [[John Williams (Reverend)|Rev. John Williams]] who wrote about his captive experience in The Redeemed Captive.<ref>{{cite book|last=Williams|first=John|title=The Redeemed Captive Returning to Zion|date=1989|location=Bedford, MA|publisher=Applewood Books}}</ref> Like Eunice and several other children from Deerfield, Rebecca Kellogg was adopted by [[Iroquois|Haudenosaunee]] Mohawks in the town of [[Kahnawake]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Demos|first=John|title=The Unredeemed Captive: A Family Story from Early America|date=1994|publisher=Alfred Knopf|location=New York|isbn=9780394557823}}</ref> She married and she raised children.

Unlike Eunice, Rebecca Kellogg returned to British colonial territory as an older woman. She married Ben Ashley and she translated for several Congregational missionaries in Indian missions, including the [[Jonathan Edwards (theologian)|Rev. Jonathan Edwards]] at the Stockbridge Indian Mission.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|last=Howard|first=Joy A. J.|title=Rebecca Kellogg Ashley: Negotiating Identity on the Early American Borderlands, 1704-1757| encyclopedia= Women in Early America: Transnational Histories, Rethinking Master Narratives| editor= Tom Foster|publisher=[[New York University Press]]}}</ref> Edwards expressed in many letters his admiration of her faith and of her interpretation skills.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://edwards.yale.edu/archive?____pgfa=aHR0cDovL2Vkd2FyZHMueWFsZS5lZHUvY2dpLWJpbi9uZXdwaGlsby9zZWFyY2gzdA&dbname=wjeo&word=Re|title= Rebecca Kellogg Ashley|accessdate=July 20, 2014|publisher=[[Jonathan Edwards Center]], [[Yale University]]}}</ref> Although she had left Kahnawake, she often lived with the Haudenosaunee and identified as a member of the [[Mohawk people|Mohawk]]. Rebecca Kellogg Ashley died in 1757 with the [[Oneida people|Oneida]] Haudenosaunee in [[Oquaga]], New York. She did not leave any writings that are known but her life is visible in the writings of the missionaries with whom she worked. The [[Gideon Hawley|Rev. Gideon Hawley]] wrote that the Haudenosaunee “greatly lamented” her death.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.congregationallibrary.org/finding-aids/HawleyGideon1237|last=Hawley|first= Gideon|title= Missionary journals|date= 1753–1806}}</ref>

